#Text=Lofoten
#Text=Lofoten is a group of islands in the northern part of Norway .

#Text=With its postcard looking small fishing villages nestled in fjords , dotting a very rugged coast with abrupt peaks rising directly from the ocean , the archipelago is often described as one of the most scenic parts of Norway .
#Text=Towns
#Text=— a town of 4,500 citizens , and is the largest settlement in the Lofoten archipelago off the coast of northern Norway .
#Text=The town is of little touristic interest .
#Text=However , it makes a good basis ( or at least a transit point ) to explore the Lofoten archipelago .
#Text=— a compulsory stopover when traveling by bus in the Lofoten
#Text=— pronounced " Oh " , this is the southernmost town on the island of Moskenesøya in the Lofoten archipelago of Norway .
#Text=The name means simply " river " or " stream " , and the town is also known as Å i Lofoten to distinguish it from other places called Å .

#Text=A ferry to the Moskenesoya maelstrom ( a swirling circular current off the coast of the island ) , and the fishing museum are the two main attractions of the village , which sits between a picturesque lake and the North Sea , with many of the wooden buildings being built over water on stilts .
#Text=There are bikes for hire at the Youth Hostel and at Lofoten Bed and Boat ( 150 kr a day ) and some hiking paths are dotted around the surrounding area .
#Text=Nice walks include going around the Ågvatnet lake , crossing the island towards the North-West and the Stokkvikvatnet lake , or going further on the main road ( e.g. , to Reine ) .
#Text=Several ferries a day from the mainland ( Bodø ) arrive at Moskenes .
#Text=From Moskenes , you can either walk following the road ( 4.8 kilometers , an hour ) or take a bus ( several times a day , kr 40 ) .
#Text=It is best to book accommodation well ahead of your travel in Å , as everything may be fully booked during the peak season .
#Text=( PS : There is no ATM in Å .
#Text=However , major credit cards are accepted virtually anywhere , including on the bus . )
#Text=—
#Text=this fishing village is known for its incredible scenery .
#Text=—
#Text=a small fishing village on the island , with no tourist information or a supermarket ; however , there is a camping location and a car rental option near the ferry terminal .
#Text=-
#Text=a very pleasant village reached by a short bus ride or long painful walk from Svolvær .
#Text=- Lofoten 's oldest fishing village .
#Text=Great food and small shops .
#Text=It lies a little to the south-west of Svolvær , the administrative center of Vågan municipality .
#Text=The village was founded as Vågan in the early 12th century by King Øystein Magnusson , who built a church and a fishermen 's hostel there .
#Text=According to Heimskringla , there was something resembling a town there several centuries earlier — the first known town in North Norway , known as Vågar .
#Text=The Lofoten Museum , as well as the Lofoten Aquarium and the Espolin Gallery , are all in Kabelvåg .
#Text=Other destinations
#Text=The Moskstraumen , popularly known as the Maelstrom is a very powerful tidal current forming twice a day between Vaeroy and Meskenesoy .
#Text=It has been featured in many works , usually in a exaggerated form ( for instance Edgar Allan Poe 's Descent into the Maelstrom ) .
#Text=Captain Ahab in Hermann Melville 's famous Moby-Dick mentions the maelstrom .
#Text=In Jules Verne 's Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Sea the submarine encounters the whirlpool .
#Text=It is unusual because it occurs in open sea .
#Text=Simply do not go there and expect giant whirlpools ...
#Text=Trollfjord - banned to navigation in spring because of falling rock but otherwise visited on the southbound voyage of the Hurtigruten .
#Text=Otherwise take a boat trip from Svolvær .
#Text=It is so narrow that the Hurtigrute boats , except for the very newest , have to do a three point turn .
#Text=Islands
#Text=Hinnøya ( southwestern part )
#Text=Austvågøy ( southern part )
#Text=Gimsøy
#Text=Vestvågøy
#Text=- Vestvågøy is a municipality and island in the county of Nordland in northern Norway .
#Text=It has a population of 10,764 people , making it the most populated area in the regions of Lofoten and Vesterålen .
#Text=Flakstadøy
#Text=Moskenesøya
#Text=Røst
#Text=Værøy is a small island around six hours from Bodø by ferry ( via Moskenes ) and around 2 hours by ferry from Moskenes .
#Text=The island has a mountainous ridge running through the centre and flat farmland below the mountains .
#Text=It is famous both for its scenery and the abundance of puffins who nest here over the summer .
#Text=Understand
#Text=At 68°N , the Lofoten archipelago is well above the Arctic Circle , and at the same latitude as Greenland or the northern parts of Alaska .
#Text=However , it enjoys a relatively mild climate due to the circulation of the Gulf Stream , and temperatures up to 23°C in the summer are not uncommon .
#Text=Still , it remains a subarctic destination , the weather changes fast , and even in the summer it may get cold .
#Text=When the sun is not shining a sweater is recommended .
#Text=Reciprocally the winter is cold , but remains bearable .

#Text=Remember , at this extreme latitude - the same as northern Siberia and northern Alaska - winters ought to be very cold , but instead of 40 below , Lofoten temperatures hover around freezing in winter , and starts to climb in April .

#Text=The Lofoten , before becoming a popular tourist retreat , was and still is a very important fishing center , especially for the special type of cod ( skrei in Norwegian ) , attracted by the rich food brought by the Gulf Stream .
#Text=At the end of the spring , thousands of tons of cod are hung to dry on wooden racks .
#Text=For at least a thousand years the very rich Lofoten cod fisheries was a key factors in the Norwegian economy .
#Text=Thousands gathered from all along the coast to take part in the winter-spring fisheries .
#Text=Key to Lofoten ’s fishery economy was the natural outdoor drying without the use of salt .

#Text=Low temperatures and constant wind is necessary for this process to be successful , further north it is too cold and further south too warm/humid , while the Lofoten island have the right conditions .
#Text=This slow drying process creates the characteristic stockfish ( Norwegian : tørrfisk , literally dry fish ) .

#Text=The dry cod was transported to and traded at the Bergen harbour thousand kilometers down the coast , the cod trade effectively created Bergen as Norway 's ( and partly Scandinavia 's ) largest and most important city .
#Text=The famous waterfront warehouses in Bergen were mostly used to store dry cod .
#Text=Still today the stockfish is exported to Italy , Croatia , Nigeria and Sweden ( the similar dry-salted cod , the klippfisk , is particularly exported to Portugal and Spain ) .
#Text=Dry cod is recorded as an important business from the Viking age , but may be older .
#Text=Long before Tromsø and Bodø existed as towns , Vågar ( Kabelvåg ) in Lofotr ( today Vestvågøy island ) was a major trading post and for centuries the only town north of Trondheim .
#Text=Bergen , Trondheim and Lofoten were the 3 business centres on Norway 's rich coast .
#Text=For centuries dry cod was Norway 's main export , up to 80 % of the trade ( as measured in currency ) was cod .
#Text=Vågar may have been Norway 's most important town until the Black Death around 1400 and the Hansa in Bergen seized monopoly in cod export .
#Text=The original town or trading post was abandoned and turned in to farmland , while nearby Kabelvåg became the new town .
#Text=The light varies very much over the seasons .
#Text=From 24 hours of daylight from May to early August to just a bluish twilight lasting three hours around noon in December and January .
#Text=In March and September , there is normal daylight hours - 12h day and 12h night .
#Text=In 1432 the venetian merchant Pietro Querini and his crew shipwrecked at Røst island after drifting for several weeks from the English Channel .
#Text=Querini supposedly introduced stockfish to the Italian cuisine .
#Text=The venetians spent 3 months with the locals and then returned to Venice where Querini produced a report for the senate there .
#Text=Querini 's unique and legendary written report was called The first circuit of paradise .
#Text=Despite the cold and dark winter , he described life in Lofoten as paradise (
#Text=" we spent 3 months in the first circuit of paradise , to the shame and disgrace of Italy " ) .
